{"title_page": "Sultanpur, Uttar Pradesh", "text_new": "{{About|the municipality in Uttar Pradesh, India|its namesake district|Sultanpur District}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}}\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2019}}\n<!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Indian cities]] for details -->\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Sultanpur\n| settlement_type                 = City\n| image_skyline                   = Sultanpur U.P Railway Station.JPG\n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = Railway Station, Sultanpur\n| nickname                        = \n| image_map                       = \n| map_alt                         = \n| map_caption                     = \n| pushpin_map                     = India Uttar Pradesh#India#Asia\n| pushpin_label_position          = right\n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = \n| coordinates                     = {{coord|26.264884|82.073125|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Sultanpur district|Sultanpur]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = [[Kusha (Ramayana)|Kush]]\n| named_for                       = \n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = Government of Uttar Pradesh\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| area_rank                       = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 95\n| population_total                = 107,640\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name=\"Census2011Gov\"/>\n| population_density_km2          = \n| population_rank                 = \n| population_demonym              = \n| demographics_type1              = [[Language]]\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]<ref name=\"langoff\">{{cite web|title=52nd REPORT OF THE COMMISSIONER FOR LINGUISTIC MINORITIES IN INDIA|url=http://nclm.nic.in/shared/linkimages/NCLM52ndReport.pdf|website=nclm.nic.in|publisher=[[Ministry of Minority Affairs]]|access-date=11 January 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525141614/http://nclm.nic.in/shared/linkimages/NCLM52ndReport.pdf|archive-date=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n| demographics1_title2            = Additional&nbsp;official\n| demographics1_info2             = [[Urdu]]<ref name=\"langoff\"/>\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 228001\n| registration_plate              = UP-44\n| blank1_name_sec1                = \n| blank1_info_sec1                = \n| website                         = {{URL|sultanpur.nic.in}}\n| footnotes                       = \n| official_name                   = \n}}\n\n'''Sultanpur''' is a city and a municipal board in [[Sultanpur District]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[Uttar Pradesh]]. Located on the right banks of the [[Gomti]]  (a major tributary of the [[Ganga|Ganga River]]), Sultanpur is the administrative headquarters of [[Sultanpur District]] and is a part of [[Faizabad Division]]. It is situated 135 kilometres east of state capital [[Lucknow]]. The common language of the people of Sultanpur is [[Awadhi]], a dialect of [[Hindi language|Hindi]].\n\nAlthough the area has been part of successive northern [[Middle kingdoms of India|Indian kingdoms]] through centuries, the recorded history of the city began in the [[Colonial India|colonial]] times. Long a center of [[Hindu]] and [[Buddhist culture]] it came under [[Muslim]] occupation in the 12th century. The city was completely destroyed during the military operations of the [[Revolt of 1857]].\n\n==History==\n{{refimprove section|date=January 2020|reason=sourced by deadlinks}}\nThe original town was situated on the left bank of the Gomti River. It is said to have been founded by [[Kusha (Ramayana)|Kush]], son of [[Rama]], and to have been named after him Kusapura or Kusabhavanpur. This ancient city has been identified by General Cunnigham as Sultanpur mentioned by Hiuentsang, the Chinese traveller. He states that there was in his time a dilapidated stupa of Ashoka and that Buddha taught here for six months. There are Buddhist remains still visible at Mahmoodpur, a village, 8&nbsp;km distant to the north-west of Sultanpur. The town subsequently fell into the hands of Bhars, who retained it until it was taken from them by Muslims in the 12th century. About seven hundred and fifty years ago, it is said, two brothers,<ref name=\"sultanpurcity.com\">http://sultanpurjankari.in/history.html</ref> Sayid Muhammad and Sayid Ala-ud-Din, horse dealer by profession, visited eastern Avadh and offered some horses for sale to Bhar Chieftains of Kusabhavanpur, who seized the horses and put the two brothers to death. This came to the ear of Ala-ud-Din Khilji, who would not allow such an outrage to pass unpunished. Gathering a mighty force, therefore, he set out for Kusabhavanpur and took revenge by killing most of the Bhars by strategem adopted after a long drawn siege. Kusabhavanpur was reduced to ashes and the town of Sultanpur, so called from the rank of the victor, rose upon its ruins. This town was finally raised to the ground during the military operations connected with the reoccupation of the province in consequence of the inhabitants having been concerned in the murder of British officers at the outbreak of the freedom struggle of 1857.<ref name=\"sultanpurcity.com\"/>\nBefore annexation a military station and cantonment were established on the right bank of the river in a village then known as Girghit but more commonly called by officials Sultanpur or Chhaoni Sarkar and by the rustic population Kampu or the Cam. The present town of Sultanpur has been developed at this site. In this city there are two parks, one maintained by Soldiers', Sailers' and Airmen's board and other privately maintained known as Chimanlal Park.<ref name=\"sultanpurcity.com\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to the [[2011 Indian Census]], Sultanpur had a total population of 107,640, of which 56,420 were males and 51,220 were females. Population within the age group of 0 to 6 years was 11,647. The total number of literates in Sultanpur was 84,080, which constituted 78.1% of the population with male literacy of 81.5% and female literacy of 74.4%. The effective literacy rate of the 7+ population of Sultanpur was 87.6%, of which male literacy was 91.6% and female literacy rate was 83.2%. The [[Scheduled Castes]] population was 7,706. Sultanpur had 17,954 households in 2011.<ref name=\"Census2011Gov\">{{cite web |title=Census of India: Sultanpur |url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/pca/SearchDetails.aspx?Id=195629 |website=www.censusindia.gov.in |accessdate=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Geography and climate==\n\nSultanpur is the headquarters of the [[Sultanpur district]], the north side of the district is bounded by [[Faizabad district]]; the south side by [[Pratapgarh district, Uttar Pradesh|Pratapgarh district]]; the west side by [[Barabanki district|Barabanki]] and [[Raebareli district]]s; and the east side by [[Azamgarh district|Azamgarh]], [[Ambedkarnagar district|Ambedkarnagar]], and [[Jaunpur district]]s. \n\nSultanpur has an average elevation of {{convert|95|m|ft}}. The geography of Sultanpur comprises plain lands, except for some regions around the Gomti River, which drains almost the whole city and district. The southern part of city drains towards the Sai River flowing through Pratapgarh district. The only significant minerals found in the region are in [[Kanker district]].\n\n==Transportation==\n===Road===\nSultanpur is connected to nearby cities through the 4-lane Lucknow to Varanasi NH 56 and the 2-lane Allahabad to Ayodhya road. UPSRTC is the major public transport apart from other commercial modes run by private agencies.\n\n===Train===\nSultanpur Railway Station (station code: SLN) connects Sultanpur to major cities in India.\n\n===Air===\nThe nearest airport to Sultanpur is [[Allahabad Airport]] which is 99 kilometers away. Lucknow Airpot is 140 km from Sultanpur and is connected by 4-lane NH 56.\n\n==Colleges==\nGeneral colleges include Maharana Pratap Post Graduate College<ref>{{cite web |title=-::- Welcome to RANA PRATAP POST GRADUATE COLLEGE Sultanpur |url=http://www.rppgsultanpur.org/aboutus.php |website=www.rppgsultanpur.org |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> and Kamla Nehru Institute for Physical and Social Sciences.<ref>{{cite web |title=:: KNIPSS Sultanpur U.P. |url=http://knipss.ac.in/ |website=knipss.ac.in |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> Engineering and management colleges include [[Kamla Nehru Institute of Technology]] and KNIPSS- Management Institute.<ref>{{cite web |title=:::KNIPSS::Management Institute Sultanpur U.P. |url=http://www.knmt.org.in/MBA/index.html |website=www.knmt.org.in |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Majrooh Sultanpuri]] - Indian Urdu poet and Bollywood lyricist\n* [[Sripati Mishra]] - former Chief Minister of Uttar Pradesh\n* [[Sanjay Singh (Indian politician)|Sanjay Singh]] - Rajya Sabha MP from Aam Aadmi Party\n* [[Kiran Prakash Yadav]] - Indian Engineering Services Officer<ref><ref></ref></ref>\n\u00a7<ref></ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.knit.ac.in Kamla Nehru Institute of Technology]\n\n{{Sultanpur district}}\n\n[[Category:Sultanpur, Uttar Pradesh| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Uttar Pradesh]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the municipality in Uttar Pradesh, India|its namesake district|Sultanpur District}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}}\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2019}}\n<!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Indian cities]] for details -->\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Sultanpur\n| settlement_type                 = City\n| image_skyline                   = Sultanpur U.P Railway Station.JPG\n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = Railway Station, Sultanpur\n| nickname                        = \n| image_map                       = \n| map_alt                         = \n| map_caption                     = \n| pushpin_map                     = India Uttar Pradesh#India#Asia\n| pushpin_label_position          = right\n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = \n| coordinates                     = {{coord|26.264884|82.073125|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Sultanpur district|Sultanpur]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = [[Kusha (Ramayana)|Kush]]\n| named_for                       = \n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = Government of Uttar Pradesh\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| area_rank                       = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 95\n| population_total                = 107,640\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name=\"Census2011Gov\"/>\n| population_density_km2          = \n| population_rank                 = \n| population_demonym              = \n| demographics_type1              = [[Language]]\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]<ref name=\"langoff\">{{cite web|title=52nd REPORT OF THE COMMISSIONER FOR LINGUISTIC MINORITIES IN INDIA|url=http://nclm.nic.in/shared/linkimages/NCLM52ndReport.pdf|website=nclm.nic.in|publisher=[[Ministry of Minority Affairs]]|access-date=11 January 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525141614/http://nclm.nic.in/shared/linkimages/NCLM52ndReport.pdf|archive-date=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n| demographics1_title2            = Additional&nbsp;official\n| demographics1_info2             = [[Urdu]]<ref name=\"langoff\"/>\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 228001\n| registration_plate              = UP-44\n| blank1_name_sec1                = \n| blank1_info_sec1                = \n| website                         = {{URL|sultanpur.nic.in}}\n| footnotes                       = \n| official_name                   = \n}}\n\n'''Sultanpur''' is a city and a municipal board in [[Sultanpur District]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[Uttar Pradesh]]. Located on the right banks of the [[Gomti]]  (a major tributary of the [[Ganga|Ganga River]]), Sultanpur is the administrative headquarters of [[Sultanpur District]] and is a part of [[Faizabad Division]]. It is situated 135 kilometres east of state capital [[Lucknow]]. The common language of the people of Sultanpur is [[Awadhi]], a dialect of [[Hindi language|Hindi]].\n\nAlthough the area has been part of successive northern [[Middle kingdoms of India|Indian kingdoms]] through centuries, the recorded history of the city began in the [[Colonial India|colonial]] times. Long a center of [[Hindu]] and [[Buddhist culture]] it came under [[Muslim]] occupation in the 12th century. The city was completely destroyed during the military operations of the [[Revolt of 1857]].\n\n==History==\n{{refimprove section|date=January 2020|reason=sourced by deadlinks}}\nThe original town was situated on the left bank of the Gomti River. It is said to have been founded by [[Kusha (Ramayana)|Kush]], son of [[Rama]], and to have been named after him Kusapura or Kusabhavanpur. This ancient city has been identified by General Cunnigham as Sultanpur mentioned by Hiuentsang, the Chinese traveller. He states that there was in his time a dilapidated stupa of Ashoka and that Buddha taught here for six months. There are Buddhist remains still visible at Mahmoodpur, a village, 8&nbsp;km distant to the north-west of Sultanpur. The town subsequently fell into the hands of Bhars, who retained it until it was taken from them by Muslims in the 12th century. About seven hundred and fifty years ago, it is said, two brothers,<ref name=\"sultanpurcity.com\">http://sultanpurjankari.in/history.html</ref> Sayid Muhammad and Sayid Ala-ud-Din, horse dealer by profession, visited eastern Avadh and offered some horses for sale to Bhar Chieftains of Kusabhavanpur, who seized the horses and put the two brothers to death. This came to the ear of Ala-ud-Din Khilji, who would not allow such an outrage to pass unpunished. Gathering a mighty force, therefore, he set out for Kusabhavanpur and took revenge by killing most of the Bhars by strategem adopted after a long drawn siege. Kusabhavanpur was reduced to ashes and the town of Sultanpur, so called from the rank of the victor, rose upon its ruins. This town was finally raised to the ground during the military operations connected with the reoccupation of the province in consequence of the inhabitants having been concerned in the murder of British officers at the outbreak of the freedom struggle of 1857.<ref name=\"sultanpurcity.com\"/>\nBefore annexation a military station and cantonment were established on the right bank of the river in a village then known as Girghit but more commonly called by officials Sultanpur or Chhaoni Sarkar and by the rustic population Kampu or the Cam. The present town of Sultanpur has been developed at this site. In this city there are two parks, one maintained by Soldiers', Sailers' and Airmen's board and other privately maintained known as Chimanlal Park.<ref name=\"sultanpurcity.com\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to the [[2011 Indian Census]], Sultanpur had a total population of 107,640, of which 56,420 were males and 51,220 were females. Population within the age group of 0 to 6 years was 11,647. The total number of literates in Sultanpur was 84,080, which constituted 78.1% of the population with male literacy of 81.5% and female literacy of 74.4%. The effective literacy rate of the 7+ population of Sultanpur was 87.6%, of which male literacy was 91.6% and female literacy rate was 83.2%. The [[Scheduled Castes]] population was 7,706. Sultanpur had 17,954 households in 2011.<ref name=\"Census2011Gov\">{{cite web |title=Census of India: Sultanpur |url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/pca/SearchDetails.aspx?Id=195629 |website=www.censusindia.gov.in |accessdate=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Geography and climate==\n\nSultanpur is the headquarters of the [[Sultanpur district]], the north side of the district is bounded by [[Faizabad district]]; the south side by [[Pratapgarh district, Uttar Pradesh|Pratapgarh district]]; the west side by [[Barabanki district|Barabanki]] and [[Raebareli district]]s; and the east side by [[Azamgarh district|Azamgarh]], [[Ambedkarnagar district|Ambedkarnagar]], and [[Jaunpur district]]s. \n\nSultanpur has an average elevation of {{convert|95|m|ft}}. The geography of Sultanpur comprises plain lands, except for some regions around the Gomti River, which drains almost the whole city and district. The southern part of city drains towards the Sai River flowing through Pratapgarh district. The only significant minerals found in the region are in [[Kanker district]].\n\n==Transportation==\n===Road===\nSultanpur is connected to nearby cities through the 4-lane Lucknow to Varanasi NH 56 and the 2-lane Allahabad to Ayodhya road. UPSRTC is the major public transport apart from other commercial modes run by private agencies.\n\n===Train===\nSultanpur Railway Station (station code: SLN) connects Sultanpur to major cities in India.\n\n===Air===\nThe nearest airport to Sultanpur is [[Allahabad Airport]] which is 99 kilometers away. Lucknow Airpot is 140 km from Sultanpur and is connected by 4-lane NH 56.\n\n==Colleges==\nGeneral colleges include Maharana Pratap Post Graduate College<ref>{{cite web |title=-::- Welcome to RANA PRATAP POST GRADUATE COLLEGE Sultanpur |url=http://www.rppgsultanpur.org/aboutus.php |website=www.rppgsultanpur.org |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> and Kamla Nehru Institute for Physical and Social Sciences.<ref>{{cite web |title=:: KNIPSS Sultanpur U.P. |url=http://knipss.ac.in/ |website=knipss.ac.in |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> Engineering and management colleges include [[Kamla Nehru Institute of Technology]] and KNIPSS- Management Institute.<ref>{{cite web |title=:::KNIPSS::Management Institute Sultanpur U.P. |url=http://www.knmt.org.in/MBA/index.html |website=www.knmt.org.in |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Majrooh Sultanpuri]] - Indian Urdu poet and Bollywood lyricist\n* [[Sripati Mishra]] - former Chief Minister of Uttar Pradesh\n* [[Sanjay Singh (Indian politician)|Sanjay Singh]] - Rajya Sabha MP from Aam Aadmi Party\n* [[Kiran Prakash Yadav]] - Indian Engineering Services Officer<ref><ref></r