ell, Mitch}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American people of Scotch-Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Baptists from Alabama]]\n[[Category:Baptists from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:County judges in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:DuPont Manual High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Federalist Society members]]\n[[Category:Kentucky lawyers]]\n[[Category:Kentucky Republicans]]\n[[Category:Leadership Institute alumni and associates]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Sheffield, Alabama]]\n[[Category:People with polio]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Louisville, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Republican Party United States senators]]\n[[Category:Right-wing populism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sons of the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:Southern Baptists]]\n[[Category:United States congressional aides]]\n[[Category:United States senators from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:University of Kentucky College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Louisville alumni]]\n[[Category:Climate change denial]]\n", "name_user": "Ben76266", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mitch_McConnell"}
{"title_page": "Highwayman's hitch", "text_new": "{{Infobox knot\n| name = Highwayman's hitch\n| names = Highwayman's hitch, draw hitch, Highwayman\u2019s cutaway, Bank Robbers Knot, Getaway hitch or Quick-release knot\n| image = Highwayman's Hitch.jpg\n| caption = A Highwayman's hitch tied around a wooden pole\n| type = hitch\n| type2 =\n| strength = \n| origin = \n| related = [[Tumble hitch]], Mooring Hitch\n| releasing = Non-jamming\n| uses = Quick-release, draw loop hitch\n| caveat = Potentially unstable, especially when tied around large objects\n| abok_number = \n| conway_notation = \n| ab_notation = \n}}\n\nThe '''Highwayman\u2019s hitch''' is a quick-release draw [[List of hitch knots|hitch]] used for temporarily securing a load that will need to be released easily and cleanly.<ref name=\"budcomp\">{{Citation|first=Geoffrey|last=Budworth|title=The Complete Book of Knots|location=London|publisher=Octopus|year=1997|page=73}}</ref>  The hitch can be untied with a tug of the working end, even when under tension. The highwayman's hitch can be tied in the middle of a rope, and so the working end does not need to be passed around the anchor when tying or releasing.<ref name=\"aksday\">{{citation|first=Cyrus Lawrence|last=Day|title=The Art of Knotting and Splicing|edition=1st|location=New York|publisher=Dodd, Mead &Co.|year=1947|pages=114\u2013115}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe hitch was called the '''highwayman's cutaway''' in 1947 by Cyrus L. Day.  He related that, according to Hal McKail, the knot was attributable to the notorious 18th-century English [[highwayman]] [[Dick Turpin]].  Day's book, however, suggested it for use as a quick-release [[Mooring (watercraft)|mooring]] hitch for [[solo sailing]].<ref name=\"aksday\"/>\n\nWhile the knot is alleged to have actually been used by highwaymen,<ref name=\"horsecarriage\">{{Citation|last1=Meier|first1=Joel F.|last2=Viola|first2=Mitchell A.|title=Camp Counseling: Leadership and Programming For the Organized Camp|publisher=Brown & Benchmark|year=1993}}</ref> this claim is rejected by knot expert Geoffrey Budworth, who stated, \"there is no evidence to substantiate the reputation of the highwayman's hitch as a quick-getaway-knot for robbers on horseback.\"<ref name=\"budcomp\"/>\n\n==Tying==\nThe knot is three [[Bight (knot)|bights]] that each successively lock the previous one: \n#the first one, in the middle of the rope, wraps around the pole, \n#the second one (called the toggle bight) is a bight of the standing part locking the first one so the pole is held tight, and \n#the third one (called the slip-tuck) is a bight of the working part (slack end) locking the second bight.\n\nThe locking actions are achieved by reaching through each bight to pull the next one through.\n\nThe knot has to be finished by pulling the standing part tight to ensure that it holds.\n\n==Weakness==\nUntil the knot is tightened and properly dressed, the highwayman's hitch has little holding power.\nThe highwayman's hitch is susceptible to capsizing when the pole is substantially larger than the rope diameter. The failure occurs because the second bight sees the force of the standing part, but is held in place by the working part, which has no tension. When capsizing, tension on the standing part pulls the second bight through the first bight. This drags the slip-tuck through, and will release the hitch if the third bight isn't long enough.\n \nAlternatives to the highwayman's hitch have been devised to mitigate collapse when tied around large objects.\n\n==Alternatives==\nOne simple improvement is to repeat the second and third bights i.e. one more bight of the standing part and then one more bight of the working part, each successively locking the previous bight; this has the disadvantage of requiring longer rope from both parts.\n\nAnother technique is to twist each bight before reaching through it for the next locking byte; the disadvantage here is the difficulty of tightening afterwards.\n\nIn his book Outdoor Knots, Clyde Soles presents one of Dan Lehman's revisions to the highwayman's hitch that is simple and effective, naming it the \"slip-free hitch\".<ref name=\"outdoor knots\">{{cite book|last1=Soles|first1=Clyde|title=The outdoor knots book : hikers, campers, climbers, kayakers|date=2004|publisher=Mountaineers Books|location=Seattle (WA)|isbn=9780898869620|edition=1st|pages=143\u2013144}}</ref>  One simply rearranges the trio of bights so that the heavily loaded bight in the standing part will surround, rather than go through, the next-made bight; the finishing slipped-tuck bight will thus go through the 2nd-made bight, and so be less severely loaded.  As the frame against which this rope toggle is nipped is entirely parts of the knot (and not depending upon proximity to the hitched object), this revision avoids the capsizing vulnerability of the highwayman's hitch.\n\nThe Notable Knot Index recommends the [[tumble hitch]] as a more stable hitch.  It's a similar hitch, but less prone to capsizing because the main part remains passive and the locking is done by two successive bights of the working part (no end needed) wrapping around both the standing part and the post/pole before locking the previous bight.<ref>{{Cite web|publisher=Notable Knot Index|url=http://notableknotindex.webs.com/tumblehitch.html|title=The Tumble Hitch|accessdate=2012-02-25}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of knots]]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://gumroad.com/l/RgaLM cheap highwayman's knot 3d model]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Knots}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Highwayman's Hitch}}\n[[Category:Hitch knots]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox knot\n| name = Highwayman's hitch\n| names = Highwayman's hitch, draw hitch, Highwayman\u2019s cutaway, Bank Robbers Knot, Getaway hitch or Quick-release knot\n| image = Highwayman's Hitch.jpg\n| caption = A Highwayman's hitch tied around a wooden pole\n| type = hitch\n| type2 =\n| strength = \n| origin = \n| related = [[Tumble hitch]], Mooring Hitch\n| releasing = Non-jamming\n| uses = Quick-release, draw loop hitch\n| caveat = Potentially unstable, especially when tied around large objects\n| abok_number = \n| conway_notation = \n| ab_notation = \n}}\n\nThe '''Highwayman\u2019s hitch''' is a quick-release draw [[List of hitch knots|hitch]] used for temporarily securing a load that will need to be released easily and cleanly.<ref name=\"budcomp\">{{Citation|first=Geoffrey|last=Budworth|title=The Complete Book of Knots|location=London|publisher=Octopus|year=1997|page=73}}</ref>  The hitch can be untied with a tug of the working end, even when under tension. The highwayman's hitch can be tied in the middle of a rope, and so the working end does not need to be passed around the anchor when tying or releasing.<ref name=\"aksday\">{{citation|first=Cyrus Lawrence|last=Day|title=The Art of Knotting and Splicing|edition=1st|location=New York|publisher=Dodd, Mead &Co.|year=1947|pages=114\u2013115}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe hitch was called the '''highwayman's cutaway''' in 1947 by Cyrus L. Day.  He related that, according to Hal McKail, the knot was attributable to the notorious 18th-century English [[highwayman]] [[Dick Turpin]].  Day's book, however, suggested it for use as a quick-release [[Mooring (watercraft)|mooring]] hitch for [[solo sailing]].<ref name=\"aksday\"/>\n\nWhile the knot is alleged to have actually been used by highwaymen,<ref name=\"horsecarriage\">{{Citation|last1=Meier|first1=Joel F.|last2=Viola|first2=Mitchell A.|title=Camp Counseling: Leadership and Programming For the Organized Camp|publisher=Brown & Benchmark|year=1993}}</ref> this claim is rejected by knot expert Geoffrey Budworth, who stated, \"there is no evidence to substantiate the reputation of the highwayman's hitch as a quick-getaway-knot for robbers on horseback.\"<ref name=\"budcomp\"/>\n\n==Tying==\nThe knot is three [[Bight (knot)|bights]] that each successively lock the previous one: \n#the first one, in the middle of the rope, wraps around the pole, \n#the second one (called the toggle bight) is a bight of the standing part locking the first one so the pole is held tight, and \n#the third one (called the slip-tuck) is a bight of the working part (slack end) locking the second bight.\n\nThe locking actions are achieved by reaching through each bight to pull the next one through.\n\nThe knot has to be finished by pulling the standing part tight to ensure that it holds.\n\n==Weakness==\nUntil the knot is tightened and properly dressed, the highwayman's hitch has little holding power.\nThe highwayman's hitch is susceptible to capsizing when the pole is substantially larger than the rope diameter. The failure occurs because the second bight sees the force of the standing part, but is held in place by the working part, which has no tension. When capsizing, tension on the standing part pulls the second bight through the first bight. This drags the slip-tuck through, and will release the hitch if the third bight isn't long enough.\n \nAlternatives to the highwayman's hitch have been devised to mitigate collapse when tied around large objects.\n\n==Alternatives==\nOne simple improvement is to repeat the second and third bights i.e. one more bight of the standing part and then one more bight of the working part, each successively locking the previous bight; this has the disadvantage of requiring longer rope from both parts.\n\nAnother technique is to twist each bight before reaching through it for the next locking byte; the disadvantage here is the difficulty of tightening afterwards.\n\nIn his book Outdoor Knots, Clyde Soles presents one of Dan Lehman's revisions to the highwayman's hitch that is simple and effective, naming it the \"slip-free hitch\".<ref name=\"outdoor knots\">{{cite book|last1=Soles|first1=Clyde|title=The outdoor knots book : hikers, campers, climbers, kayakers|date=2004|publisher=Mountaineers Books|location=Seattle (WA)|isbn=9780898869620|edition=1st|pages=143\u2013144}}</ref>  One simply rearranges the trio of bights so that the heavily loaded bight in the standing part will surround, rather than go through, the next-made bight; the finishing slipped-tuck bight will thus go through the 2nd-made bight, and so be less severely loaded.  As the frame against which this rope toggle is nipped is entirely parts of the knot (and not depending upon proximity to the hitched object), this revision avoids the capsizing vulnerability of the highwayman's hitch.\n\nThe Notable Knot Index recommends the [[tumble hitch]] as a more stable hitch.  It's a similar hitch, but less prone to capsizing because the main part remains passive and the locking is done by two successive bights of the working part (no end needed) wrapping around both the standing part and the post/pole before locking the previous bight.<ref>{{Cite web|publisher=Notable Knot Index|url=http://notableknotindex.webs.com/tumblehitch.html|title=The Tumble Hitch|accessdate=2012-02-25}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of knots]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Knots}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Highwayman's Hitch}}\n[[Category:Hitch knots]]\n", "name_user": "Zaripov999", "label": "safe", "comment": "add external link to 3d model", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Highwayman%27s_hitch"}
{"title_page": "Elsy Borders", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=May 2017}}{{Infobox person\n| name               = Elsy Borders\n| image              = ElsyBorders1939.jpg\n| alt                = Face of a white woman, wearing a hat and glasses.\n| caption            = Elsy Borders, from a 1939 British Path\u00e9 newsreel flim.\n| birth_name         = Elsy Florence Eva Kreher\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1905|1|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Lambeth]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|1971|8|14|1905|1|14|df=y}}\n| death_place        = [[Exeter]]\n| nationality        = British\n| occupation         = Activist for housing reform\n}}\n\n'''Elsy Florence Eva Borders,''' n\u00e9e Kreher, (14 January 1905 \u2013 14 August 1971) was a campaigner for [[Building code|building standards]] who led a large mortgage strike in [[England]] in the 1930s.\n\n== Early life ==\nElsy Kreher was born in 1905, in Lambeth, the daughter of John Engelbert Kreher and Edith Eliza Morley Kreher. Her father was a waiter.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite ODNB|id=104306|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-104306|title=Borders [''n\u00e9e'' Kreher], Elsie Florence Eva [Elsy] (1905\u20131971), housing activist|last=Reynolds|first=K. D.|date=2013|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn 1937, Elsy Borders and her husband withheld payments and sued the [[building society]] that held the mortgage on their newly-built semi-detached house on the Coney Hall estate near [[West Wickham]] in [[Kent]], for misrepresenting the house's \"slap-dash\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47070407/views-on-mrs-borderss-house/|title=Views on Mrs. Borders's House|date=1938-10-21|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-21|url-status=live|pages=3|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> workmanship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/mortgage-strikes|title=The Mortgage Strikes|last=McCulloch|first=Andrew|date=6 June 2001|website=History Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Jackson|first=Alan A.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Ye1GDwAAQBAJ&lpg=PT177&dq=Elsy%20Borders&pg=PT177#v=onepage|title=Semi-Detached London: Suburban Development, Life and Transport, 1900-39|date=2018-01-12|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-351-17512-8|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Samy|first=Antoninus|url=https://books.google.com/?id=LznKDAAAQBAJ&lpg=PA156&dq=Elsy%20Borders&pg=PA156#v=onepage|title=The Building Society Promise: Access, Risk, and Efficiency 1880-1939|date=2016|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-878780-8|location=|pages=156\u2013157|language=en}}</ref> She studied law at the [[London School of Economics]], in order to represent herself in court in 1938.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Powers|first=Alan|url=https://books.google.com/?id=A2v079OhHJwC&lpg=PA64&dq=Elsy%20Borders&pg=PA64#v=onepage|title=Britain|date=2007|publisher=Reaktion Books|isbn=978-1-86189-281-2|location=|pages=64|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47070148/mrs-borders-calls-a-neighbour-and-an/|title=Mrs. Borders Calls a Neighbour and an Architect|date=1938-10-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-21|url-status=live|pages=7|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>  \"Not the least occasion for the notoriety of the Borders case,\" commented an American observer, \"was the fact that Elsie Borders herself must be a picturesque character, the wife of a taxi-cab operator, who acted a her own counsel in the case and apparently her own press agent. She proved to be a good one in both cases.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Russell|first=Horace|date=1939|title=The Borders Case|journal=The Journal of Land & Public Utility Economics|volume=15|issue=2|pages=225\u2013227|doi=10.2307/3158131|jstor=3158131|issn=1548-9000}}</ref> \"'Portia' Borders became the heroine of thousands of Britons who pay high rents for grimy kennels or find their shiny new houses falling apart,\" explained ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine in 1939.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,761772,00.html|title=Foreign News: After Elsy|date=1939-07-31|work=Time|access-date=2020-03-21|language=en-US|issn=0040-781X}}</ref> She appealed the case up to the [[House of Lords]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47069911/mrs-borders-to-appeal/|title=Mrs. Borders to Appeal|date=1939-02-14|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-21|pages=11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47070281/mrs-borderss-appeal-allowed/|title=Mrs. Borders's Appeal Allowed|date=1940-01-30|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-21|url-status=live|pages=3|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> but it was finally lost in 1941.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47069725/mrs-borders-loses-her-appeal/|title=Mrs. Borders Loses Her Appeal|date=1941-05-10|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-21|url-status=live|pages=5|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nIn a related case, Borders successfully represented her husband in a [[Defamation|libel]] case brought by the housing society.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47070520/verdict-for-mr-borders/|title=Verdict for Mr. Borders|date=1939-03-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-21|url-status=live|pages=10|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nElsy Borders was a member of the [[Communist Party of Great Britain|Communist party]], and helped to form the Federation of Tenants\u2019 and Residents\u2019 Association (FTRA).<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsshopper.co.uk/news/10688529.west-wickham-heroine-from-borders-of-insanity/|title=West Wickham heroine from 'borders of insanity'|last=Ogley|first=Bob|date=20 September 2013|website=News Shopper|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> They led a mortgage strike in [[England]], joined by 3,000 home-owners. The FTRA held its first national convention in 1939, in Birmingham. That year, an amendment to the Building Societies Act, introduced by [[Ellen Wilkinson]], addressed some of the FTRA's concerns; however, the Act's final revision increased protections for the building societies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/property/3291336/Inside-story-insanity.html|title=Inside story: insanity|last=Wilkes|first=Roger|date=24 July 2001|website=The Telegraph|publisher=|via=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishpathe.com/video/VLVA5SWQ1QPQ2YNG5ZBPLN0DHCCLH-POLITICS-GOVERNMENT-BILL-AGAINST-JERRY-BUILDING-PLANNED/query/Jerry|title=Politics: Government Bill Against Jerry-Building Planned|last=|first=|date=6 March 1939|website=British Path\u00e9|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nElsy Kreher married James Walter (Jim) Borders in 1926; her husband was a London cabby. They had a daughter, Pamela, born in 1930. The couple jokingly called their house \"Insanity\", and themselves \"the Borders of Insanity.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> The Borders moved away from London in 1940, and divorced in 1944. Elsy and her daughter moved to [[Exeter]] during [[World War II]].  Elsy Borders died in 1971, aged 66 years, in Exeter.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*Graham Stevenson (26 January 2011). [https://grahamstevenson.me.uk/2011/01/26/borders-elsy-and-jim/ \"Borders Elsy and Jim\"]. A blog post about the Borders case.\n*Mudlark121 (13 January 2018). [https://pasttenseblog.wordpress.com/2018/01/13/today-in-london-housing-history-elsy-borders-goes-to-court-in-west-wickham-mortgage-strike-1938/ \"Today in London housing history: Elsy Borders goes to court in West Wickham mortgage strike, 1938\"] ''Past Tense: London Radical Histories and Possibilities''. A blog post on Elsy Borders.\n*[https://www.shutterstock.com/editorial/image-editorial/elsy-borders-of-west-wickham-who-is-representing-herself-in-court-against-the-building-society-who-are-seeking-top-repossess-her-home-box-666-100202168-ajpg-5766292a A 1938 news photograph of the Borders family], by Reg Warhurst, at Shutterstock.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Borders, Elsy}}\n[[Category:1905 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:English activists]]\n[[Category:English women activists]]\n[[Category:People from Lambeth]]\n[[Category:People from West Wickham]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=May 2017}}{{Infobox person\n| name               = Elsy Borders\n| image              = ElsyBorders1939.jpg\n| alt                = Face of a white woman, wearing a hat and glasses.\n| caption            = Elsy Borders, from a 1939 British Path\u00e9 newsreel flim.\n| birth_name         = Elsy Florence Eva Kreher\n| birth_date         = 14 January 1905\n| birth_place        = Lambeth\n| death_date         = 14 August 1971\n| death_place        = Exeter\n| nationality        = British\n| occupation         = Activist for housing reform\n}}\n\n'''Elsy Florence Eva Borders,''' n\u00e9e Kreher, (14 January 1905 \u2013 14 August 1971) was a campaigner for [[Building code|building standards]] who led a large mortgage strike in [[England]] in the 1930s.\n\n== Early life ==\nElsy Kreher was born in 1905, in Lambeth, the daughter of John Engelbert Kreher and Edith Eliza Morley Kreher. Her father was a waiter.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite ODNB|id=104306|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-104306|title=Borders [''n\u00e9e'' Kreher], Elsie Florence Eva [Elsy] (1905\u20131971), housing activist|last=Reynolds|first=K. D.|date=2013|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn 1937, Elsy Borders and her husband withheld payments and sued the [[building society]] that held the mortgage on their newly-built semi-detached house on the Coney Hall estate near [[West Wickham]] in [[Kent]], for misrepresenting the house's \"slap-dash\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47070407/views-on-mrs-borderss-house/|title=Views on Mrs. Borders's House|date=1938-10-21|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-21|url-status=live|pages=3|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> workmanship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/mortgage-strikes|title=The Mortgage Strikes|last=McCulloch|first=Andrew|date=6 June 2001|website=History Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Jackson|first=Alan A.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Ye1GDwAAQBAJ&lpg=PT177&dq=Elsy%20Borders&pg=PT177#v=onepage|title=Semi-Detached London: Suburban Development, Life and Transport, 1900-39|date=2018-01-12|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-351-17512-8|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Samy|first=Antoninus|url=https://books.google.com/?id=LznKDAAAQBAJ&lpg=PA156&dq=Elsy%20Borders&pg=PA156#v=onepage|title=The Building Society Promise: Access, Risk, and Efficiency 1880-1939|date=2016|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-878780-8|location=|pages=156\u2013157|language=en}}</ref> She studied law at the [[London School of Economics]], in order to represent herself in court in 1938.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Powers|first=Alan|url=https://books.google.com/?id=A2v079OhHJwC&lpg=PA64&dq=Elsy%20Borders&pg=PA64#v=onepage|title=Britain|date=2007|publisher=Reaktion Books|isbn=978-1-86189-281-2|location=|pages=64|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47070148/mrs-borders-calls-a-neighbour-and-an/|title=Mrs. Borders Calls a Neighbour and an Architect|date=1938-10-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-21|url-status=live|pages=7|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>  \"Not the least occasion for the notoriety of the Borders case,\" commented an American observer, \"was the fact that Elsie Borders herself must be a picturesque character, the wife of a taxi-cab operator, who acted a her own counsel in the case and apparently her own press agent. She proved to be a good one in both cases.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Russell|first=Horace|date=1939|title=The Borders Case|journal=The Journal of Land & Public Utility Economics|volume=15|issue=2|pages=225\u2013227|doi=10.2307/3158131|jstor=3158131|issn=1548-9000}}</ref> \"'Portia' Borders became the heroine of thousands of Britons who pay high rents for grimy kennels or find their shiny new houses falling apart,\" explained ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine in 1939.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,761772,00.html|title=Foreign News: After Elsy|date=1939-07-31|work=Time|access-date=2020-03-21|language=en-US|issn=0040-781X}}</ref> She appealed the case up to the [[House of Lords]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47069911/mrs-borders-to-appeal/|title=Mrs. Borders to Appeal|date=1939-02-14|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-21|pages=11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47070281/mrs-borderss-appeal-allowed/|title=Mrs. Borders's Appeal Allowed|date=1940-01-30|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-21|url-status=live|pages=3|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> but it was finally lost in 1941.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47069725/mrs-borders-loses-her-appeal/|title=Mrs. Borders Loses Her Appeal|date=1941-05-10|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-21|url-status=live|pages=5|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nIn a related case, Borders successfully represented her husband in a [[Defamation|libel]] case brought by the housing society.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47070520/verdict-for-mr-borders/|title=Verdict for Mr. Borders|date=1939-03-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-21|url-status=live|pages=10|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nElsy Borders was a member of the [[Communist Party of Great Britain|Communist party]], and helped to form the Federation of Tenants\u2019 and Residents\u2019 Association (FTRA).<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsshopper.co.uk/news/10688529.west-wickham-heroine-from-borders-of-insanity/|title=West Wickham heroine from 'borders of insanity'|last=Ogley|first=Bob|date=20 September 2013|website=News Shopper|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> They led a mortgage strike in [[England]], joined by 3,000 home-owners. The FTRA held its first national convention in 1939, in Birmingham. That year, an amendment to the Building Societies Act, introduced by [[Ellen Wilkinson]], addressed some of the FTRA's concerns; however, the Act's final revision increased protections for the building societies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/property/3291336/Inside-story-insanity.html|title=Inside story: insanity|last=Wilkes|first=Roger|date=24 July 2001|website=The Telegraph|publisher=|via=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishpathe.com/video/VLVA5SWQ1QPQ2YNG5ZBPLN0DHCCLH-POLITICS-GOVERNMENT-BILL-AGAINST-JERRY-BUILDING-PLANNED/query/Jerry|title=Politics: Government Bill Against Jerry-Building Planned|last=|first=|date=6 March 1939|website=British Path\u00e9|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nElsy Kreher married James Walter (Jim) Borders in 1926; her husband was a London cabby. They had a daughter, Pamela, born in 1930. The couple jokingly called their house \"Insanity\", and themselves \"the Borders of Insanity.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> The Borders moved away from London in 1940, and divorced in 1944. Elsy and her daughter moved to [[Exeter]] during [[World War II]].  Elsy Borders died in 1971, aged 66 years, in Exeter.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*Graham Stevenson (26 January 2011). [https://grahamstevenson.me.uk/2011/01/26/borders-elsy-and-jim/ \"Borders Elsy and Jim\"]. A blog post about the Borders case.\n*Mudlark121 (13 January 2018). [https://pasttenseblog.wordpress.com/2018/01/13/today-in-london-housing-history-elsy-borders-goes-to-court-in-west-wickham-mortgage-strike-1938/ \"Today in London housing history: Elsy Borders goes to court in West Wickham mortgage strike, 1938\"] ''Past Tense: London Radical Histories and Possibilities''. A blog post on Elsy Borders.\n*[https://www.shutterstock.com/editorial/image-editorial/elsy-borders-of-west-wickham-who-is-representing-herself-in-court-against-the-building-society-who-are-seeking-top-repossess-her-home-box-666-100202168-ajpg-5766292a A 1938 news photograph of the Borders family], by Reg Warhurst, at Shutterstock.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Borders, Elsy}}\n[[Category:1905 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:English activists]]\n[[Category:English women activists]]\n[[Category:People from Lambeth]]\n[[Category:People from West Wickham]]\n", "name_user": "Hqb", "label": "safe", "comment": "{{birth/death date}} in infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elsy_Borders"}
{"title_page": "Jarrad Hearman", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| image_size          = 150 \n| name                = Jarrad Hearman\n| image               = Jarrad Studio Pic 2.jpg\n| caption             = \n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = \n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1980|6|26}}\n| birth_place         = Australia\n| occupation          = Recording, Mixing and Mastering Engineer\n| instrument          = Guitar\n| years_active        = 2003\u2013present\n| genre           = {{flatlist|\n* [[Pop music|Pop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[Grime music|Grime]]\n* [[electronic dance music|Dance]]\n* [[Alternative music|Alternative]]\n* [[Rock music|Rock]]\n}}\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = [[Katy B]], [[Sin\u00e9ad Harnett]], [[Tinie Tempah]], [[Kali Uchis]], [[Novelist (rapper)|Novelist]], Kideko\n| website         = {{URL|jarradhearman.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Jarrad Hearman''' (born 26 June 1980) is a [[Sound recording and reproduction|Recording]], [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|Mixing]] and [[Mastering Engineer]], based in [[London]], [[England]].  He has worked with artists including [[Katy B]], [[Sin\u00e9ad Harnett]], [[Fetty Wap]], [[Becky G]], [[Nadia Rose]], [[Tinie Tempah]], [[Kali Uchis]], [[Keys N Krates]], [[Craig David]], [[P Money]], [[Novelist (rapper)|Novelist]], [[Tinashe]], [[Wretch 32]], [[Ian Brown]], [[Taj Mahal (musician)|Taj Mahal]], and [[Toumani Diabate]].\n\nHe recorded and mixed the 2014 [[Katy B]] [[album]], ''[[Little Red (album)|Little Red]]'', which reached number one on the [[UK Albums Chart]],<ref>{{cite web\n | url =http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/6425/katy%20b/\n | title =Katy B Full Official Chart History\n | last =B\n | first =Katy\n | website =Officialcharts.com\n | publisher = \n | access-date =30 March 2016\n | quote = }}</ref> as well as the [[KDA (DJ)|KDA]] Single \"[[Turn the Music Louder (Rumble)]]\" which debuted at number one on the UK Singles Chart in 2015.<ref>{{cite web\n | url =http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/20151023/7501/\n | title =Archive Chart: 2015-10-29\n | last = \n | first = \n | website =Officialcharts.com\n | publisher = \n | access-date =30 March 2016\n | quote = }}</ref>  In other roles he has worked with the likes of [[Jay Z|Jay-Z]], [[Kanye West]], [[The Prodigy]], [[Will-I-Am]], [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]], [[John Butler (musician)|John Butler]], and [[Dirty Three]], and mixed TV performances for [[Channel 4]], the [[BBC]], and [[MTV UK]].\n\n==Discography==\n\n* 2020 - [[Waze & Odyssey]] vs Tommy Theo \"Always\" Single (Mixing & Mastering Engineer)\n* 2020 - Rika \"Doses\" Single (Mixing & Mastering Engineer)\n* 2019 - Sin\u00e9ad Harnett \"Lessons In Love\" Album (Mixing)\n* 2019 - Rika \"Hold On To Me\" Single (Mixing & Mastering Engineer)\n* 2019 - Blaise x Nono x [[Sweetie Irie]] \"Good Body\" Single (Mixing & Mastering Engineer)\n* 2019 - Salute \"Conditions III\" EP (Mixing & Mastering Engineer) \n* 2019 - Luke Burr \"Keep On Loving\" Single (Mixing & Mastering Engineer)\n* 2019 - Sin\u00e9ad Harnett \"Leo Bear\" Single (Mixing)\n* 2019 - Luke Burr \"Heaven\" Single (Mixing & Mastering Engineer)\n* 2019 - ARUN \"Y.D.E.K\" Single (Mixing & Mastering Engineer)\n* 2018 - Suspect \"F-About\" Single (Mixing & Mastering Engineer)\n* 2018 - Nathan Dawe ft Jaykae & Br-C \"Cheatin\" (UKG Remix)\n* 2018 - Sin\u00e9ad Harnett \"Lessons\" Single (Mixing & Mastering Engineer)\n* 2018 - Kid Enigma & [[Riton (musician)]] \"Dangerous\"(Mixing & Mastering Engineer + Additional Production)\n* 2018 - Salute \"Nostalgia '96\" (Mixing & Mastering Engineer)\n* 2018 - Sin\u00e9ad Harnett & JD. Reid \"System\" Single (Mixing)\n* 2018 - James Smith \u201cT-Shirts\u201d Single (Mixing & Mastering Engineer)\n* 2018 - Conducta ft Liv Dawson & Courage \"Sleep\" Singl